<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="120" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1073,1305,1424]" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">
COMMENTS: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1887" box="[363,600,1305,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitarius">
<emphasis box="[363,600,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Megarthrus solitarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp. These" authorityYear="1887" box="[660,805,1305,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zunilensis">
<emphasis box="[660,805,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">M. zunilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are apparently the only Neotropical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1829" box="[292,418,1337,1360]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[292,418,1337,1360]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">Megarthrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the abdominal tergite VIII forming a medioapical projection in the female. These two species differ, however, in most of the other sexual characters. See discussion under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bruch" authorityYear="1940" box="[506,638,1401,1424]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ogloblini">
<emphasis box="[506,638,1401,1424]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="120">M. ogloblini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
